🐛 Bugs found + fixed (Session 14)

Bug 1: Migration tracker drift, again (parallel AI track). supabase migration up refused to apply 20260514000000 because 20260513150349_add_feedback_to_quiz_attempts.sql (an AI-track migration) was on disk but never recorded in supabase_migrations.schema_migrations — leaving a gap. Diagnosed it was Case A (the feedback column already existed on quiz_attempts — the migration's effect WAS applied, just not tracked). Fixed with the Bug-2-from-Session-13 repair pattern: manually INSERT the tracker row, then `supabase migration up` applied only the new migration cleanly. The file itself is idempotent (`add column if not exists`) so re-running would've been safe anyway, but recording-as-applied is the correct fix. Lesson: this is the SECOND time the AI track caused tracker drift. The pre-migration check protocol works and caught it — but the AI track keeps writing migrations without recording them. See coordination note below.

Bug 2: `.or()` with a timestamp in the filter string silently matched zero rows. First cut of the last_active_at middleware update used `.or('last_active_at.is.null,last_active_at.lt.' + isoString)` as a self-throttle. PostgREST's `.or()` string parser chokes on the `:` characters in an ISO timestamp; the filter matched nothing, the UPDATE no-op'd, fire-and-forget swallowed it. Lesson: never put a raw ISO timestamp inside a PostgREST `.or()` filter string. If you need a timestamp comparison in a throttle, do it in SQL (RPC) where comparison actually works — or drop the throttle.

Bug 3: profiles has NO self-service FOR UPDATE RLS policy. After removing the `.or()`, an unconditional `.update({last_active_at}).eq('id', user.id)` STILL didn't write. Root cause: the middleware's Supabase client runs as the user (anon key + user cookies) under RLS, and profiles' only UPDATE policy is "Admins can update all profiles". profiles_self_service is FOR SELECT, not UPDATE — I'd assumed it covered update from the name. A regular user's UPDATE matched zero rows and silently no-op'd. Fix: 20260514010000_touch_last_active.sql — a SECURITY DEFINER function that bypasses RLS but can ONLY ever set last_active_at for auth.uid(). NOT a blanket self-update RLS policy, because Postgres RLS restricts which ROWS an UPDATE touches, not which COLUMNS — a blanket policy would let a student rewrite their own `role` to 'admin' (privilege escalation). The function is the entire attack surface and does exactly one harmless thing. Lesson: before assuming a user can write their own row, check `SELECT polname, polcmd FROM pg_policy WHERE polrelid = '<table>'::regclass` — polcmd, not the policy name. r=select, w=update, a=insert, d=delete, *=all. For "let a user touch one specific field of their own row," a SECURITY DEFINER RPC is the correct pattern.

