⚠️ How to give me code (Session 15)

Same as Session 14, with the markdown-wrap point promoted because it mattered this session:

- ALWAYS markdown-wrap .tsx/.ts as .md with ```tsx / ```ts fenced code blocks — the user cannot reliably render raw .tsx/.ts inline. This is not optional; plain .tsx output was unreadable for them this session.
- Whole-file paste/replacement for any TSX. Never heredoc for TSX.
- For server-side .ts: heredocs OK; avoid Promise<Array<{...}>>.
- Just put the whole code, don't tell the user to make small edits.
- For multi-file changes: dump everything in one message, or in labeled batches.
- Don't run the user's code through other AIs.
- For migration apply or smoke-test runs, GIVE EVERYTHING IN ONE MESSAGE.
- Before writing SQL referencing tables outside this session's work, ask the user to run \d <table> first.
- For RLS-affecting work, ALSO check the policy COMMANDS, not just names: `SELECT polname, polcmd FROM pg_policy WHERE polrelid = '<table>'::regclass` (Session 14 Bug 3 — a policy named *_self_service was select-only, not update).
- For component prop signatures, ALWAYS check the actual file before guessing.
- When the user pastes an existing file, treat it as authoritative.
- For new SQL trigger functions: use clock_timestamp() for updated_at columns, not now().
- Server-component → client-component props: JSON-serializable only. No function props.
- For Python heredocs that emit JS string-escapes: use raw triple-quoted strings or write to a temp file, NOT heredoc-with-escapes (Session 13 Bug 1).
- RUN THE MANDATORY PRE-MIGRATION DRIFT CHECK before writing any migration (see Important Contracts above). The AI track has caused tracker drift twice now.
- Never put a raw ISO timestamp inside a PostgREST .or()/.filter() string (Session 14 Bug 2).
- DO NOT modify AI-track files without confirming with the user first: src/lib/ai/*, src/lib/ai/prompts/*, src/lib/actions/aiGenerations.ts, src/app/api/ai/*, src/components/teacher/ai/*.
- DO NOT use xlsx for new spreadsheet exports — use xlsx-js-style.
- DO NOT bypass RLS with service-role except for the calendar .ics route. New SECURITY DEFINER functions are OK when properly scoped (like touch_last_active) but require the same scrutiny — the function body is the entire attack surface.
- Audit/review tasks: do a bounded findings-report pass FIRST (read + report, severity-ranked), let the user choose what to fix, THEN fix. Don't sprawl. (This worked well for the admin audit in Session 14.)

Session 14 in numbers: 4 queue items shipped, 2 new migrations, 2 new server-action files, 2 new components, 3 bugs caught + codified (1 migration drift, 2 in the last_active_at debugging arc), 1 incorrect audit finding self-corrected, ~13 file touches. The last_active_at feature took 3 attempts (filter bug → RLS gap → SECURITY DEFINER RPC) — the lesson got codified. 🎉